# C) Plot the poisson distribution function for cumulative probability of cars sold per-week vs number of cars sold perweek.
from scipy.stats import poisson
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
#
# Random variable representing number of restaurants
# Mean number of occurences of restaurants in 10 KM is 2
#
X = [0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6 ,7 ]
lmbda = 3
#
# Probability values
#
poisson_pd = poisson.cdf(X, lmbda)
#
# Plot the probability distribution
#
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(8, 6))
ax.plot(X, poisson_pd, 'bo', ms=8, label='poisson cdf')
plt.ylabel("Probability Of Cars Sold", fontsize="18")
plt.xlabel("X - No. of Cars Sold", fontsize="18")
plt.title("Poisson Distribution -cumulative probability of cars sold per-week vs number of cars sold perweek", fontsize="18")

# Scenario : The probability a student is in honors math is 0.25, in honors science is 0.30, and in both is 0.20.  

# Question What is the probability a student is in at least one honors class?
# formula used  P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A and B) 
probability_math = 0.25
probability_science = 0.30
probability_both = 0.20

probability_of_student_in_atleast_one_honour_class = ((probability_math+probability_science) - probability_both)

print('A) What is the probability a student is in at least one honors class %1.2f'%probability_of_student_in_atleast_one_honour_class)

#According to weight given score to each team 0 ,1 or 2
# 0 - Highest per forming team
# 1 - Average performing team
# 2 - lowest per forming team
conditions = [
    ((data1['weight'] == 5.0) | (data1['weight'] == 6.0)),
    ((data1['weight'] == 4.0) | (data1['weight'] == 3.0) | (data1['weight'] == 2.0)),
    ((data1['weight'] == 1.0) | (data1['weight'] == 0.0))
    ]
                     

# create a list of the values we want to assign for each condition
values = [0, 1, 2]

# create a new column and use np.select to assign values to it using our lists as arguments
data1['Performer'] = np.select(conditions, values)

from scipy.stats import norm
#Null hypthesis
 #H0: p1 = p2  
 #H0: p1 = p2 
 #H0: p1 = p2  
#Ha no difference between  comparing the proportion of companies that are operating between winners and contestants

#Ha: p1 > p2
